==English==

===Etymology===
From Revelation 9:1–12.<ref>{{R:King James Version|Revelation|9|1|passage=And the fift Angel sounded, and I saw a starre fall from heauen vnto the earth: and to him was giuen the key of the bottomlesse pitte.}}</ref>

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[pit]] with no visible ([[infinite]]) [[bottom]].
#: {{syn|en|abyss}}
# {{lb|en|biblical}} [[hell|Hell]].
#* '''1769''', ''The Bible'', [[s:Bible (King James)|King James Version, Oxford Standard Text]], ''Revelation'', [[s:Bible (King James)/Revelation#Chapter 9|9:11]],
#*: And they had a king over them, which is the angel of the '''bottomless pit''', whose name in the Hebrew tongue is Abaddon, but in the Greek tongue hath his name Apollyon.
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} An [[endless]] resource or supply.
#* '''1994''': ''Asia in the Making of Europe'', Donald Frederick Lach
#*: Lipsius was replaced at Leyden by {{w|Joseph Justus Scaliger}} (1540-1609), the French Protestant scholar who was known to contemporaries as "the '''bottomless pit''' of erudition."
# {{lb|en|figuratively}} A person with an apparently [[boundless]] appetite; an entity or problem which consumes seemingly endless resources.
#: {{syn|en|money pit|black hole}}
#* '''2006''': ''The Club For Growth: Bottomless Pit'' ([[blog]] entry), Phillip Rodokanakis
#*: In other words, we will continue throwing good money after bad, trying to feed a '''bottomless pit's''' [[insatiable]] appetite for taxpayer dollars.

